    Speaking of exchange,
I'm exchanging this video for anything other than this video .

Exchanges don't centralize a cryptocurrency or are a means of centralization. Its a means of saying "hey I'll buy your bitcoin from you at current market price" sort of like the fish you buy at a nice restaurant. If it was centralized, Coinbase could mint and control how much bitcoin is circulated as well as alter the public ledger. Also, Bitcoin would be only limited to U.S. control. In short exchanges only well....exchange but to be decentralized means no one person, country, or entity can change, alter, or forge the currency as a whole or the blockchain integrity. I also watched "Banking on Bitcoin" and of course, it shows people the good, bad and in between effects of investing in it. From what I understand thus far, I don't think users should necessarily see it as a get-rich-quick scheme because different people have a mix of different results. For example, there are some who actually DO make a huge amount of money; there are some who make a LITTLE more based on their skills in using it, and there are those who unfortunately LOSE all of their bitcoin or assets because of either hacking or misused bitcoin in some illegal way; so it basically varies. What I did so far was open a separate bank account at a different bank, so that if I ever do decide to go along with investing in bitcoin, I can use my bank information from that alternative bank with less money in it than my REGULARLY used bank just in case I lose anything.
